class Solution:
    def countOfAtoms(self, formula: str) -> str:
        stack = [collections.Counter()]
        i, n = 0, len(formula)
        while i < n:
            if formula[i] == '(':
                stack.append(collections.Counter())
                i += 1
            elif formula[i] == ')':
                top = stack.pop()
                i += 1
                j = i
                while i < n and formula[i].isdigit():
                    i += 1
                mult = int(formula[j:i] or 1)
                for atom in top:
                    stack[-1][atom] += top[atom] * mult
            else:
                j = i
                i += 1
                while i < n and formula[i].islower():
                    i += 1
                atom = formula[j:i]
                j = i
                while i < n and formula[i].isdigit():
                    i += 1
                cnt = int(formula[j:i] or 1)
                stack[-1][atom] += cnt
        counts = stack[0]
        return ''.join(atom + (str(counts[atom]) if counts[atom] > 1 else '')
                       for atom in sorted(counts))
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n log n) where n is the length of the formula (due to sorting the atoms)
space complexity: O(n) for the stack and counters
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses a stack to handle nested parentheses: each level gets its own counter. When a closing parenthesis is encountered, the counts inside are multiplied by the following number and merged into the parent level. After processing, atoms are sorted alphabetically and concatenated into the required string.

